### Description

In a angular test I am trying to test simple async validator for a signal form, but even after applying TestBed.tick() signal form seems to be in invalid state. Workaround seems to be  await Promise.resolve(); twice.

 It also works if I replace  `TestBed.tick(); `with `tick()` & `fakeAsync`, but we are moving away from `zone`.


```ts
 it('should be valid - not working',  () => {
      TestBed.runInInjectionContext(() => {
        f = form(model, path => {
            asyncValValidator(path);
        });
      });
      model.set('aaaa');
      TestBed.tick();
      expect(f().valid()).toBeTrue(); // fails, needs tick() from fakeAsync
    });

    it('should be valid works workarund', async () => {
        TestBed.runInInjectionContext(() => {
          f = form(model, path => {
              asyncValValidator(path);
          });
        });

        model.set('aaaa');
        TestBed.tick();
        await Promise.resolve();
        await Promise.resolve(); // workound for fakeAsync + tick()

        expect(f().valid()).toBeTrue(); // needs fakeAsync to work or Promise.resolve twice
      });
```

